    <name>
      <text>Finding the determinant, adjacent and inverse of a matrix</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>Let \(A={@matrix_A@}\). Find each of the following.</p>

<br>

<table>
  <tr>
    <td width="100px">(a) \(A_{11} = \)</td>
    <td>&nbsp; [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]]</td>
  </tr>
</table>
<p>[[feedback:prt1]]</p>

<table>
  <tr>
    <td width="100px">(b) \(Adj(A) = \)</td>
    <td>&nbsp; [[input:ans2]] [[validation:ans2]]</td>
  </tr>
</table>
<p>[[feedback:prt2]]</p>

<br>

<p>(c) \(\text{det}(A)=\) [[input:ans3]] [[validation:ans3]]</p>
<p>[[feedback:prt3]]</p>

<br>

<table>
  <tr>
    <td width="100px">(d) \(A^{-1} = \)</td>
    <td>&nbsp; [[input:ans4]] [[validation:ans4]]</td>
  </tr>
</table>
<p>[[feedback:prt4]]</p>]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[<h3>Worked solution</h3>

<p>(a) The matrix \(A_{ij}\) is the matrix \(A\) with the \(i^{\text{th}}\) row and \(j^{\text{th}}\) column removed. Therefore,</p>
<p style="margin-left: 30px">\(A_{11} = {@ta_1@}\)</p>

<br>

<p>(b) The adjoint of a matrix, \(Adj(A)\) is given by the transpose of the matrix of cofactors, \([C_{ij}(A)]\).
<br>The entries of the matrix of cofactors are given by,<p>
<p style="margin-left:30px">\(C_{ij}(A) = (-1)^{i+j} \text{det}(A_{ij})\)</p>

<br>

<p>Using part (a), we have that,</p>
<p style="margin-left:30px">\(C_{11}(A) = (-1)^{1+1} \text{det}(A_{11}) = \text{det} \left( {@ta_1@} \right) = {@ta_5@}\)</p>

<p>Similarly, we can compute, \(A_{12} = 
{@matrix([matrix_A[2][1], matrix_A[2][3]], [matrix_A[3][1], matrix_A[3][3]])@}
\)
<br>Therefore,</p>
<p style="margin-left: 30px">\(C_{12}(A) = - \text{det} \left( {@matrix([matrix_A[2][1], matrix_A[2][3]], [matrix_A[3][1], matrix_A[3][3]])@} \right) 
= {@ta_6@}\)</p>

<br>

<p>We continue to compute the remaining values to get the matrix of cofactors,</p>
<p style="margin-left: 30px">\([C_{ij}(A)] ={@mistake_ta2@}\) </p>

<p>Then, the adjoint of matrix \(A\) is given by,</p>
<p style="margin-left:30px">\(Adj(A) = [C_{ij}(A)]^{T}= {@ta_2@}\)</p>

<br>

<p>(c) We can expand down the first column of the matrix to compute the determinant, remembering to alternate between addition and subtraction,</p>
<p style="margin-left: 30px">\(\begin{align*}
\text{det}(A) 

&= {@matrix_A[1][1]@} \cdot \text{det}(A_{11}) - {@matrix_A[2][1]@} \cdot \text{det}(A_{21}) + {@matrix_A[3][1]@} \cdot \text{det}(A_{31}) \\

&= {@matrix_A[1][1]@} \cdot {@if ta_2[1][1]<0 then "(" else ""@}{@ta_2[1][1]@}{@if ta_2[1][1]<0 then ")" else ""@} 
- {@matrix_A[2][1]@} \cdot {@if -ta_2[1][2]<0 then "(" else ""@}{@-ta_2[1][2]@}{@if -ta_2[1][2]<0 then ")" else ""@} 
+ {@matrix_A[3][1]@} \cdot {@if ta_2[1][3]<0 then "(" else ""@}{@ta_2[1][3]@}{@if ta_2[1][3]<0 then ")" else ""@} \\

&= {@ta_3@}
\end{align*}\)</p>

<br>

<p>(d) We obtain the inverse of a matrix, \(A\) by dividing the matrix \(\text{adj}(A)\) by the constant \(\text{det}(A)\),
<p style="margin-left: 30px">\(A^{-1} = \frac{1}{\text{det}(A)} \cdot \text{adj}(A)
={@ta_4@}\)]]></text>
